description: This installment focuses on learning to set boundaries with the people we love. What if six friends want to hang out for a July 4th BBQ? What if someone wants to come inside our homes but we’re not comfortable with that? Adults and kids need to know how to explain their boundaries, but sometimes that’s so hard. The panelists talk about good language to use, how to avoid judging the needs of others, and how we can be social without making each other uncomfortable.
title: 10.Taking Care with Meredith Goldstein

description: Watch Boston Globe Love Letters advice columnist Meredith Goldstein in the next installment of Taking Care with Joani Geltman, clinician, parenting coach, and author of “A Survival Guide to Parenting Teens.”  Throughout these sessions, Meredith has learned how difficult quarantine life has been for teens, in particular.  Joani  provides insight on how parents can  help their teens during this time, and how teens can deal with their parents.
title: 7.Taking Care with Meredith Goldstein

description: This episode of Taking Care is a Q&A with Boston College’s David Blustein, who studies work and psychology – as in, what unemployment means to people, and how our jobs contribute to our mental health. He wrote a book called “The Importance of Work in an Age of Uncertainty," which came out in 2019 – before this pandemic. Blustein talks to Love Letters columnist Meredith Goldstein about how we can take care of ourselves if we’re working, out of work, deemed essential (and in harm’s way), or considering a career change now that the world and our priorities have shifted. Get David's book here.
title: 9.Taking Care with Meredith Goldstein

description: Twitter is what’s happening and what people are talking about, all around the world. From breaking news and entertainment, to sports and politics. If it's happening, it's happening first on Twitter. First and foremost, Twitter is a platform for news. Peter Greenberger, Global Director of News, will outline how the platform is connecting the dots between newsrooms and developers.  You will also hear from the Twitter Platform team about the future of the @TwitterAPI, highlighting recent improvements (and new features) to the Direct Message APIs. We'll dive into specific use cases for our new data platform and publisher tools, as well. We're excited to share Twitter’s tools with the NYC community so that we can continue to better innovate and build, together.
title: #TapIntoTwitter NYC

description: The Globe asked best-selling author Ben Mezrich to write a novella, a work of fiction, to be published exclusively in the Globe and on Globe.com. In “The Mechanic,” Mezrich takes us on a taut journey through his hometown of Boston, from the halls of Harvard to the glitz of a waterfront casino to the ominously silent galleries of a museum and a critical patch of local history we thought we knew, but apparently do not. Watch the virtual event to hear Ben Mezrich talk about 'The Mechanic' in a conversation moderated by Cynthia Needham, Assistant Managing Editor of The Boston Globe.
title: 'The Mechanic' Virtual Discussion with Author Ben Mezrich

description: As Black Lives Matter protests dominate the national stage, theaters shuttered by COVID-19 remain closed indefinitely. The hiatus is a chance for the theater industry to consider its past, present, and future, and its role in the racial justice movement. What forms does racism take in the theater? How must the industry change in terms of the environment and opportunities created for Black actors, directors, playwrights, and audiences? How can this moment of national reckoning be reflected onstage? Globe critic Don Aucoin talks with four leading Black theater artists about their experiences and insights, as well as their hopes for their own work and for theater in Boston.
title: Creating anti-racist theater

description: Watch reporters Evan Allen and Neil Swidey as well as editor Steve Wilmsen in a discussion of "The Virus's Tale", a narrative of the missteps and hesitations that helped make Massachusetts one of the states hardest hit by the coronavirus. title: The Virus's Tale: A Live Discussion

description: In the cultural world, museums were bound to reopen first. A model built on solitary contemplation in big, roomy buildings means they're somewhat suited to our new socially distanced order. By all accounts, museums have an enormous impact on the Massachusetts economy, contributing more than a billion dollars annually while boosting Boston's bona fides as an intellectual hub. But as museums reopen, these nonprofits will also serve as microcosms of how much life has changed over the past three months. Murray Whyte speaks with four of Boston’s museum leaders on the road ahead as their organizations emerge from pandemic-imposed limbo.

description: Sporting News is the oldest sporting publication in the United States. A weekly from its debut in 1886 until 2008, it was for decades known informally as “The Bible of Baseball” and was essential reading for players, officials, and fans. Beginning in the 1940s, it began to cover a wider array of sports and, in the more recent past, has given prominence to professional football. As sports media have proliferated in print, on the airwaves, and online, the Sporting News has undergone several transformations as it has struggled to maintain a unique presence in a very competitive environment and to attract sufficient numbers of readers and advertisers.
